10.1016/j.ebcr.2017.11.003

LAYSUMM

TITLE

Development and use of the art therapy seizure assessment sculpture on an inpatient epilepsy monitoring unit

PARAGRAPH

This article covers the development and use of the Seizure Assessment Sculpture (SAS) was created to encourage patients to create a sculpture representing the physical, emotional, and psychological effects of their seizures.

Over time a pattern was noted in the way the seizures were depicted.

Patients with psychogenic non-epileptic seizures (PNES) created sculptures differently than people with epilepsy.

The knowledge gained from the way the art was created, and what the patients had to say about it may help to treat both disorders in the future.